Question
Hi all,
I just want a sanity check regarding the declaration of mat props in a vector. I believe I am doing things correctly, however I am seeing a seg fault during material property declaration.
Here is a description of my method,
For the class def:
#include "Material.h"
#include "BaseNameInterface.h"
#include "MaterialProperty.h"
#include "RankTwoTensorForward.h"

class TestClass : public Material, public BaseNameInterface
public:
  static InputParameters validParams();
  TestClass(const InputParameters & parameters);
protected:
  std::vector<ADMaterialProperty<RankTwoTensor> *> _matvec;

and constructor:
TestClass::TestClass(const InputParameters & parameters):
    Material(parameters),
    BaseNameInterface(parameters)
{
  for (unsigned int i = 0; i <= 5; i++)
        _matvec[i] = &Material::declareADProperty<RankTwoTensor>("test" + std::to_string(i));
}


This is just a paired-down example, but I want to double-check that this is the correct way to do this.
Thank you!

I actually did do that; I just failed to include it in this mock-up example. My bad.
So what I actually have is
TestClass::TestClass(const InputParameters & parameters):
    Material(parameters),
    BaseNameInterface(parameters)
{
 _matvec.size(5);
  for (unsigned int i = 0; i <= 5; i++)
        _matvec[i] = &Material::declareADProperty<RankTwoTensor>("test" + std::to_string(i));
}

Hi all,
I have a problem which I have encountered in the past that is coming up again. I use gmsh for meshing.
When I create a 2D mesh, and define 1D physical groups (lines), MOOSE is able to recognize those lines as boundaries and do things like apply Neumann conditions, use VectorPostProcessors like SideValueSampler, etc.
However, when I create a 3D mesh and define 1D physical groups, I get the error:
(VectorPostprocessors/upper_right_z_disp/boundary):
    the following side sets (ids) do not exist on the mesh: sample_location (19)

    MOOSE distinguishes between "node sets" and "side sets" depending on whether
    you are using "Nodal" or "Integrated" BCs respectively. Node sets corresponding
    to your side sets are constructed for you by default.

    Try setting "Mesh/construct_side_list_from_node_list=true" if you see this error.
    Note: If you are running with adaptivity you should prefer using side sets.

This only shows up for 1D physical groups. 2D physical groups/boundaries work fine. Also, "construct_side_list_from_node_list=true" does not change anything.
Based off of this behavior, If I understand correctly, the way it works is that "sides" can only be 1 dimension less than the dimension of the mesh. But then what do I do if I want to apply a line load on a 3D mesh? Or in my case (reason for making this post), sample a value along a curved line? LineValueSampler can't work for me there because that can only define straight lines.
Interestingly enough, a 0D physical group had no issues applying a Dirichlet BC.
